WHEREAS, George Washington modeled religious freedom, as demonstrated in his
Letter to the Touro Synagogue, and recognized the moral contradiction of slavery, freeing those
he enslaved upon his death as an acknowledgment of its incompatibility with the ideals of the
republic; and
WHEREAS, upon George Washington's death on December 14, 1799, at his beloved
home of Mount Vernon, President John Adams declared, "His example is now complete, and it
will teach wisdom and virtue to magistrates, citizens, and men, not only in the present age, but
in future generations, as long as our history shall be read."; and
WHEREAS, Tennessee's residents are encouraged to honor George Washington's
legacy by visiting Mount Vernon, which provides invaluable educational opportunities, including
teachers institutes that equip educators to share his story and ideals with future generations;
now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we commemorate February 22, 2025, as George
Washington Day in Tennessee and encourage all citizens to reflect on and celebrate the
enduring contributions of George Washington to the founding and preservation of our nation.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
